# A ([[short#Adjective|short]]) [[cessation]] of [[combat#Noun|combat]]; a [[ceasefire]], a [[truce]]. {{defdate|from late 17th c.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Francis Lieber|authorlink=Francis Lieber|chapter=[[w:Lieber Code|Instructions for the Government of Armies of the United States in the Field [General Order No. 100]]]|title=General Orders Affecting the Volunteer Force|series=Adjutant General’s Office|seriesvolume=1863|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[w:United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]]|date=24 April 1863|year_published=1864|section=section VIII (Armistice—Capitulation)|page=83|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=RkAtAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA83|oclc=45457866|passage=135. An '''armistice''' is the cessation of active hostilities for a period agreed upon between belligerents. It must be agreed upon in writing, and duly ratified by the highest authorities of the contending parties. / 136. If an '''armistice''' be declared, without conditions, it extends no further than to require a total cessation of hostilities, along the front of both belligerents.|lang=en}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Edward N[icolae] Luttwak|authorlink=Edward Luttwak|chapter=The Coming Together of Opposites|title=Strategy: The Logic of War and Peace|edition=revised and enlarged|location=Cambridge, Mass.; London|publisher=The Belknap Press of {{w|Harvard University Press}}|year=2002|year_published=2003 (2nd printing)|section=part I (The Logic of Strategy)|pages=59–60|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mgYMXSyn5p0C&pg=PA59|isbn=978-0-674-00508-2|passage=It has also become routine to interrupt wars in more lasting fashion by imposing '''armistices'''. Again, unless directly followed by successful peace negotiations, '''armistices''' perpetuate the state of war indefinitely because they shield the weaker side from the consequences of refusing the concessions needed for peace. {{...}} '''Armistices''' in themselves are not way stations to peace but rather frozen wars.}}
# A [[formal]] [[agreement]], especially between [[nation]]s, to [[end#Verb|end]] combat.
#* {{quote-book|author={{w|John Debrett}}, compiler|chapter=Preface|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=E-9YAAAAcAAJ&pg=PR1|title=A Collection of State Papers, Relative to the War against France now Carrying on by Great Britain and the Several Other European Powers;{{nb...|Containing Authentic Copies of Treaties, Conventions, Proclamations, Manifestoes, Declarations, Memorials, Remonstrances, Official Letters, Parliamentary Papers, London Gazette Accounts of the War, &c. &c. &c. Many of which have Never before been Published.}}|location=London|publisher=Printed for J[ohn] Debrett,{{nb...|opposite Burlington House, Piccadilly.}}|year=1797|volume=V|oclc=520784460|passage=The Fifth Volume of this Collection makes its appearance at the moſt eventful period of the war—it includes, therefore, matter of the higheſt importance, and contains all the official documents reſpecting the late Negotiation—the war between this country and Spain, the progreſs of the French arms in Italy and Germany—the '''armiſtices''' and treaties concluded with the German and Italian powers— {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|author=[John Lowell Jr.]|authorlink=John Lowell Jr. (lawyer)|chapter=No. IV. The Several Proposals for an Armistice Considered.|title=Perpetual War, the Policy of Mr. [[w:James Madison|Madison]].{{nb...|Being a Candid Examination of His Late Message to Congress, so far as Respects the Following Topicks&nbsp;… viz. the Pretended Negotiations for Peace&nbsp;… the Important and Interesting Subject of a Conscript Militia&nbsp;… and the Establishment of an Immense Standing Army of Guards and Spies, under the Name of a Local Volunteer Force. [...] By a New-England Farmer.}}|location=Boston, Mass.|publisher=Printed by C[hester] Stebbins|year=1813|page=17|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=-71EAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA16|oclc=191266103|passage=The government of Great-Britain lost no time after the war was known, in making to our cabinet proposals for an '''armistice'''. Those proposals were like all propositions between equal states, perfectly reciprocal. They require of us to ''suspend hostilities only'', in consideration of suspending hostilities on their part. They are silent as to [[impressment]]s—and would any person inquire why? It may be answered, that impressments had never been presented to Great-Britain ''as in themselves the cause of war''— {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|author=John Malam|authorlink=John Malam|chapter=The Day Armistice was Signed|editor=Mary-Jane Wilkins|title=11 November 1918: The World War I Armistice|series=Dates with History|location=London|publisher=CherrytreeBooks, Evans Brothers|year=2003|pages=12–13|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=oHADk3dTZv4C&pg=PA1902|isbn=978-1-84234-200-8|passage=The day '''armistice''' was signed {{...}} At five o'clock on the morning of 11 November 1918, a group of high-ranking German politicians and military officers entered a railway carriage in the Forest of Compiègne. They were met by delegates from the countries with which they had been at war. Three days earlier the French, British and Americans had prepared an ''armistice'' document which they demanded the Germans accept within three days. Inside the carriage the Germans signed the surrender document put before them. The document signalled that the war would stop in six hours' time, at the eleventh hour of the eleventh day of the eleventh month of 1918.}}
# ''Often in the form'' '''{{l|en|Armistice}}''': the armistice agreement [[sign#Verb|signed]] between the [[Allies]] and [[Germany]] on 11 [[November]] 1918 to end [[World War I]]; {{lb|en|by extension}} the end of World War I. {{defdate|from 1918}}
#* {{quote-book|author=David Hunter Miller|authorlink=David Hunter Miller|chapter=Supreme War Council, February 12, 1919|title=The Drafting of the Covenant|location=New York, N.Y.; London|publisher={{w|G. P. Putnam's Sons}}{{nb...|The Knickerbocker Press}}|year=1928|volume=2|page=165|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=YxyPAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA165|oclc=491280262|passage=[W]hat was to be the future policy of the Associated Governments in regard to the renewal of the '''Armistice''': should the '''Armistice''' constantly be renewed, with new clauses and new conditions, or were the final naval and military terms to be drawn up immediately and imposed on the enemy.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Nick Stafford|authorlink=Nick Stafford|title=Armistice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XkNhBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT258|location=London|publisher=[[w:Quercus (publisher)|Quercus]]|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84916-081-0|passage=Philomena passed another line of shabby soldiers waiting patiently at a soup kitchen. Months after the '''Armistice''' the war wasn't over. {{...}} Dan was killed after the '''Armistice'''&nbsp;– an armistice is only a truce, it isn't the end. Is the '''Armistice''' technically ended? What will come after the '''Armistice'''&nbsp;– the peace? That would be nice.}}
#* {{quote-web|title=Armistice Day: Macron and Merkel mark end of World War One|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46165903|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111065102/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46165903|archivedate=11 November 2018|work={{w|BBC News}}|date=10 November 2018|passage=French President {{w|Emmanuel Macron}} and German Chancellor {{w|Angela Merkel}} have left their own mark of reconciliation at the start of events to mark the centenary of the end of World War One. They signed a book of remembrance in a railway carriage identical to the one in which the 1918 '''Armistice''' was sealed. {{...}} Mrs Merkel became the first German leader since World War Two to visit the forest near the town of Compiègne in northern France where the '''Armistice''' was signed.}}

